# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: zebra-patterning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] In photography, the **35 mm equivalent focal length** is a measure of the angle of view for a particular combination of a camera lens and film or image sensor size.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] The term is popular because in the early years of digital photography, most photographers experienced with interchangeable lenses were most familiar with the 35 mm film format.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] On any 35 mm film camera, a 28 mm lens is a wide-angle lens, and a 200 mm lens is a long-focus lens.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] The 35 mm equivalent focal length of a particular lens–sensor combination is the focal length that one would need for a 35 mm film camera to obtain the same angle of view.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Two lens-sensor combinations with the same 35 mm equivalent focal length are expected to have the same angle of view.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Most commonly, the 35 mm equivalent focal length is based on equal *diagonal* angle of view.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] This definition is also in the CIPA guideline DCG-001.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Alternatively, it may sometimes be based on *horizontal* angle of view.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] 35 mm equivalent focal lengths are calculated by multiplying the actual focal length of the lens by the crop factor of the sensor.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Quoted 35 mm equivalent focal lengths typically ignore depth of field (DOF), which depends on both focal length and aperture.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] The DOF of smaller sensors is deeper at a given f number, due to the smaller absolute aperture diameters corresponding to shorter focal length lenses.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Equivalent depth of field can be calculated the same way using the crop factor.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] For example, a 50mm f/2 lens on a 2× crop factor Micro Four Thirds camera would be equivalent to a 100 mm (= 2×50 mm) f/4 (= f/(2×2)) lens on a full-frame digital SLR in terms of field of view, depth of field, total light gathered, and diffraction effects.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] However for the purposes of exposure calculations the aperture does not change for different sensor sizes.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] A standard 35 mm film image is 36 mm wide by 24 mm tall (35 mm refers to the height of the film including the perforations for film transport), and the diagonal is 43.3 mm.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] For historical reasons, sensor size specifications such as 1/2.5" do not match the actual sensor size, but are a bit larger (typically about a factor of 1.5) than the actual sensor diagonal.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] This is because these sensor size specifications refer to the size of a camera tube, while the usable sensor size is about 2/3 of the size of the tube.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Tubes are not used on digital cameras, but the same specifications are used.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Apart from the width- and diagonal-based 35 mm equivalent focal length definitions, there is a third definition: *EFL* = 50 *f* /*d* mm.
[src:zebra-patterning/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] However, it is not clear to what extent this definition is used.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] There has been no commonly used definition of the term "abstract photography".
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] The term is both inclusive of a wide range of visual representations and explicit in its categorization of a type of photography that is visibly ambiguous by its very nature.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Many photographers, critics, art historians and others have written or spoken about abstract photography without attempting to formalize a specific meaning.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Photographer and Professor of Psychology John Suler, in his essay *Photographic Psychology: Image and Psyche,* said that "An abstract photograph draws away from that which is realistic or literal.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] It draws away from natural appearances and recognizable subjects in the actual world.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Some people even say it departs from true meaning, existence, and reality itself.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] It stands apart from the concrete whole with its purpose instead depending on conceptual meaning and intrinsic form....Here's the acid test: If you look at a photo and there's a voice inside you that says 'What is it?'….Well, there you go.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] German photographer and photographic theorist Gottfried Jäger used the term "concrete photography", playing off the term "concrete art", to describe a particular kind of abstract photography.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] More recently conceptual artist Mel Bochner hand wrote a quote from the Encyclopædia Britannica that said "Photography cannot record abstract ideas." on a note card, then photographed it and printed it using six different photographic processes.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] He turned the words, the concept and the visualization of the concept into art itself, and in doing so created a work that presented yet another type of abstract photography, again without ever defining the term itself.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Some of the earliest images of what may be called abstract photography appeared within the first decade after the invention of the craft.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] In 1842 John William Draper created images with a spectroscope, which dispersed light rays into a then previously unrecorded visible pattern.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] The prints he made had no reference to the reality of the visible world that other photographers then recorded, and they demonstrated photography's unprecedented ability to transform what had previously been invisible into a tangible presence.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Draper saw his images as science records rather than art, but their artistic quality is appreciated today for their groundbreaking status and their intrinsic individuality.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Another early photographer, Anna Atkins in England, produced a self-published book of photograms made by placing dried algae directly on cyanotype paper.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Intended as a scientific study, the stark white on blue images have an ethereal abstract quality due to the negative imaging and lack of natural context for the plants.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] The discovery of the X-ray in 1895 and radioactivity in 1896 caused a great public fascination with things that were previously invisible or unseen.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] In response, photographers began to explore how they could capture what could not be seen by normal human vision.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] About this same time Swedish author and artist August Strindberg experimented with subjecting saline solutions on photographic plates to heat and cold.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] The images he produced with these experiments were indefinite renderings of what could not otherwise be seen and were thoroughly abstract in their presentation.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Near the turn of the century Louis Daguerre in France tried to capture images of mental processes by pressing unexposed plates to the foreheads of sitters and urging them to project images from their minds onto the plates.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] The photographs he produced were blurry and indefinite, yet Daguerre was convinced that what he called "thought vibrations" were indistinguishable from light rays.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] During the first decade of the 20th century there was a wave of artistic exploration that hastened the transition in painting and sculpture from Impressionism and Post-Impressionism to Cubism and Futurism.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Beginning in 1903 a series of annual art exhibitions in Paris called the Salon d'Automne introduced the public to then radical vision of artists like Cézanne, Picasso, Marcel Duchamp, Francis Picabia, František Kupka, Albert Gleizes, and Jean Metzinger.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] A decade later the Armory Show in New York created a scandal by showing completely abstract works by Kandinsky, Braque, Duchamp, Robert Delaunay and others.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] The public's interest in and sometimes repulsion to abstract art was duly noted by some of the more creative photographers of the period.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] By 1910, in New York Alfred Stieglitz began to show abstract painters like Marsden Hartley and Arthur Dove at his 291 art gallery, which had previously exhibited only pictorial photography.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Photographers like Stieglitz, Paul Strand and Edward Steichen all experimented with depictive subjects photographed in abstract compositions.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] The first publicly exhibited images that are now recognized as abstract photographs were a series called *Symmetrical Patterns from Natural Forms,* shown by Erwin Quedenfeldt in Cologne in 1914.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Two years later Alvin Langdon Coburn began experimenting with a series he called *Vortographs*.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] During one six-week period in 1917 he took about two dozen photographs with a camera outfitted with a multi-faceted prism.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] The resulting images were purposely unrelated to the realities he saw and to his previous portraits and cityscapes.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] He wrote "Why should not the camera throw off the shackles of contemporary representations…?
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] In the 1920s and 1930s there was a significant increase in the number of photographers who explored abstract imagery.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] In Europe, Prague became a center of avant-garde photography, with František Drtikol, Jaroslav Rössler, Josef Sudek and Jaromír Funke all creating photographs influenced by Cubism and Futurism.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Rössler's images in particular went beyond representational abstraction to pure abstractions of light and shadow.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] László Moholy-Nagy, a leader of the Bauhaus school of modernism, experimented with the abstract qualities of the photogram.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Some photographers during this time also pushed the boundaries of conventional imagery by incorporating the visions of surrealism or futurism into their work.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Man Ray, Maurice Tabard, André Kertész, Curtis Moffat and Filippo Masoero were some of the best known artists who produced startling imagery that questioned both reality and perspective.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Both during and after World War II photographers such as Minor White, Aaron Siskind, Henry Holmes Smith and Lotte Jacobi explored compositions of found objects in ways that demonstrated even our natural world has elements of abstraction embedded in it.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Frederick Sommer broke new ground in 1950 by photographing purposely rearranged found objects, resulting in ambiguous images that could be widely interpreted.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] He chose to title one particular enigmatic image *The Sacred Wood*, after T.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] The 1960s were marked uninhibited explorations in to the limits of photographic media at the time, starting with photographers who assembled or re-assembled their own and/or found images, such as Ray K.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Metzker, Robert Heinecken and Walter Chappell.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Neumann developed chemograms, which are products of both photographic processing and painting on photographic paper.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Before the spread of computers and the use of image processing software the process of creating chemograms can be considered an early form of analog post-production, in which the original image is altered after the enlarging process.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Unlike works of digital post-production each chemogram is a unique piece.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Beginning in the late 1970s photographers stretched the limits of both scale and surface in what was then traditional photographic media that had to be developed in a darkroom.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] By the 1990s a new wave of photographers were exploring the possibilities of using computers to create new ways of creating photographs.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Photographers such as Thomas Ruff, Barbara Kasten, Tom Friedman, and Carel Balth were creating works that combined photography, sculpture, printmaking and computer-generated images.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Once computers and photography software became widely available, the boundaries of abstract photography were expanded beyond the limits of film and chemistry into almost limitless dimensions.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Any boundaries that remained between pure artists and pure photographers were eliminated by individuals who worked exclusively in photography but produced only computer-generated images.
[src:zebra-patterning/abstract-photography] Among the most well-known of the early 21st century generation were Gaston Bertin, Penelope Umbrico, Ard Bodewes, Ellen Carey, Nicki Stager, Shirine Gill, Thomas Ruff, Andrew Prokos, Wolfgang Tillmans, Kim Keever, Harvey Lloyd, and Adam Broomberg and Oliver Chanarin.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] An **active-pixel sensor** (**APS**) is an image sensor where each pixel sensor unit cell has a photodetector (typically a pinned photodiode) and one or more active transistors.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] APS sensors are used in digital camera technologies such as cell phone cameras, web cameras, most modern digital pocket cameras, most digital single-lens reflex cameras (DSLRs), mirrorless interchangeable-lens cameras (MILCs), and lensless imaging for, e.g., blood cells.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] In a **metal–oxide–semiconductor** (MOS) active-pixel sensor, MOS field-effect transistors (MOSFETs) are used as amplifiers.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] There are different types of APS, including the early NMOS APS and the now much more common complementary MOS (CMOS) APS, also known as the **CMOS sensor**.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] CMOS sensors emerged as an alternative to charge-coupled device (CCD) image sensors and eventually outsold them by the mid-2000s.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The term *active pixel sensor* is also used to refer to the individual pixel sensor itself, as opposed to an array of such individuals, the image sensor.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] In this case, the image sensor is sometimes called an *active pixel sensor imager* or *active-pixel image sensor*.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] While researching metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology, Willard Boyle and George E.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Smith discovered that an electric charge could be stored on a small MOS capacitor, which became the fundamental building block of the charge-coupled device (CCD) that they invented in 1969.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] One of the main challenges with CCD technology was its reliance on nearly perfect charge transfer during readout.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] At RCA Laboratories, a research team including Paul K.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Sadasiv in 1969 proposed a solid-state image sensor with scanning circuits using thin-film transistors (TFTs), with photoconductive film used for the photodetector.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] A low-resolution "mostly digital" N-channel MOSFET (NMOS) imager with intra-pixel amplification, for an optical mouse application, was demonstrated by Richard F.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Another type of image sensor technology that is related to the APS is the hybrid infrared focal plane array (IRFPA), designed to operate at cryogenic temperatures in the infrared spectrum.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The devices are two chips that are put together like a sandwich: one chip contains detector elements made in InGaAs or HgCdTe, and the other chip is typically made of silicon and is used to read out the photodetectors.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The exact date of origin of these devices is classified, but they were in use by the mid-1980s.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] A key element of the modern CMOS sensor is the pinned photodiode (PPD).
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] It was invented by Nobukazu Teranishi, Hiromitsu Shiraki and Yasuo Ishihara at NEC in 1980, and then publicly reported by Teranishi and Ishihara with A.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Arai in 1982, with the addition of an anti-blooming structure.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The pinned photodiode is a photodetector structure with low lag, low noise, high quantum efficiency and low dark current.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The new photodetector structure invented at NEC was given the name "pinned photodiode" (PPD) by B.C.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] In 1987, the PPD began to be incorporated into most CCD sensors, becoming a fixture in consumer electronic video cameras and then digital still cameras.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Since then, the PPD has been used in nearly all CCD sensors and then CMOS sensors.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The precursor to the APS was the passive-pixel sensor (PPS), a type of photodiode array (PDA).
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] A passive-pixel sensor consists of passive pixels which are read out without amplification, with each pixel consisting of a photodiode and a MOSFET switch.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] In a photodiode array, pixels contain a p-n junction, integrated capacitor, and MOSFETs as selection transistors.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] This was the basis for the PPS, which had image sensor elements with in-pixel selection transistors, proposed by Peter J.W.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Passive-pixel sensors were being investigated as a solid-state alternative to vacuum-tube imaging devices.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The MOS passive-pixel sensor used just a simple switch in the pixel to read out the photodiode integrated charge.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Pixels were arrayed in a two-dimensional structure, with an access enable wire shared by pixels in the same row, and output wire shared by column.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] At the end of each column was a transistor.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Passive-pixel sensors suffered from many limitations, such as high noise, slow readout, and lack of scalability.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Early (1960s–1970s) photodiode arrays with selection transistors within each pixel, along with on-chip multiplexer circuits, were impractically large.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The noise of photodiode arrays was also a limitation to performance, as the photodiode readout bus capacitance resulted in increased read-noise level.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Correlated double sampling (CDS) could also not be used with a photodiode array without external memory.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] It was not possible to fabricate active-pixel sensors with a practical pixel size in the 1970s, due to limited microlithography technology at the time.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Because the MOS process was so variable and MOS transistors had characteristics that changed over time (Vth instability), the CCD's charge-domain operation was more manufacturable and higher performance than MOS passive-pixel sensors.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The active-pixel sensor consists of active pixels, each containing one or more MOSFET amplifiers which convert the photo-generated charge to a voltage, amplify the signal voltage, and reduce noise.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The concept of an active-pixel device was proposed by Peter Noble in 1968.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] He created sensor arrays with active MOS readout amplifiers per pixel, in essentially the modern three-transistor configuration: the buried photodiode-structure, selection transistor and MOS amplifier.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The MOS active-pixel concept was implemented as the charge modulation device (CMD) by Olympus in Japan during the mid-1980s.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] This was enabled by advances in MOSFET semiconductor device fabrication, with MOSFET scaling reaching smaller micron and then sub-micron levels during the 1980s to early 1990s.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The first MOS APS was fabricated by Tsutomu Nakamura's team at Olympus in 1985.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The term *active pixel sensor* (APS) was coined by Nakamura while working on the CMD active-pixel sensor at Olympus.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The CMD imager had a vertical APS structure, which increases fill-factor (or reduces pixel size) by storing the signal charge under an output NMOS transistor.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Other Japanese semiconductor companies soon followed with their own active pixel sensors during the late 1980s to early 1990s.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Between 1988 and 1991, Toshiba developed the "double-gate floating surface transistor" sensor, which had a lateral APS structure, with each pixel containing a buried-channel MOS photogate and a PMOS output amplifier.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Between 1989 and 1992, Canon developed the base-stored image sensor (BASIS), which used a vertical APS structure similar to the Olympus sensor, but with bipolar transistors rather than MOSFETs.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] In the early 1990s, American companies began developing practical MOS active pixel sensors.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] In 1991, Texas Instruments developed the bulk CMD (BCMD) sensor, which was fabricated at the company's Japanese branch and had a vertical APS structure similar to the Olympus CMD sensor, but was more complex and used PMOS rather than NMOS transistors.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] By the late 1980s to early 1990s, the CMOS process was well-established as a well-controlled stable semiconductor manufacturing process and was the baseline process for almost all logic and microprocessors.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] There was a resurgence in the use of passive-pixel sensors for low-end imaging applications, while active-pixel sensors began being used for low-resolution high-function applications such as retina simulation and high-energy particle detectors.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] However, CCDs continued to have much lower temporal noise and fixed-pattern noise and were the dominant technology for consumer applications such as camcorders as well as for broadcast cameras, where they were displacing video camera tubes.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The CMOS active-pixel sensor, a type of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) image sensor, was developed by Mitsubishi Electric in 1992 and NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in 1993.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] It came after active-pixel sensors that were developed using PMOS technology in Japan by Toshiba.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] It had a lateral APS structure similar to the Toshiba sensor, but was fabricated with CMOS rather than PMOS transistors.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] It was the first CMOS sensor with intra-pixel charge transfer.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] In 1999, Hyundai Electronics announced the commercial production of a 800x600 color CMOS image sensor based on 4T pixel with a high performance pinned photodiode with integrated ADCs and fabricated in a baseline 0.5 um DRAM process.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Photobit's CMOS sensors found their way into webcams manufactured by Logitech and Intel, before Photobit was purchased by Micron Technology in 2001.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The CMOS sensor with PPD technology was further advanced and refined by R.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] This led to CMOS sensors achieve imaging performance on par with CCD sensors, and later exceeding CCD sensors.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] By 2000, CMOS sensors were used in a variety of applications, including low-cost cameras, PC cameras, fax, multimedia, security, surveillance, and videophones.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The video industry switched to CMOS cameras with the advent of high-definition video (HD video), as the large number of pixels would require significantly higher power consumption with CCD sensors, which would overheat and drain batteries.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Sony in 2007 commercialized CMOS sensors with an original column A/D conversion circuit, for fast, low-noise performance, followed in 2009 by the CMOS back-illuminated sensor (BI sensor), with twice the sensitivity of conventional image sensors.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] CMOS sensors went on to have a significant cultural impact, leading to the mass proliferation of digital cameras and camera phones, which bolstered the rise of social media and selfie culture, and impacted social and political movements around the world.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] By 2007, sales of CMOS active-pixel sensors had surpassed CCD sensors, with CMOS sensors accounting for 54% of the global image sensor market at the time.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] By 2012, CMOS sensors increased their share to 74% of the market.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] As of 2017, CMOS sensors account for 89% of global image sensor sales.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] In recent years, the CMOS sensor technology has spread to medium-format photography with Phase One being the first to launch a medium format digital back with a Sony-built CMOS sensor.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] In 2012, Sony introduced the stacked CMOS BI sensor.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] There have been several research activities ongoing in the field of image sensors.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] One of them is the quanta image sensor (QIS), which might be a paradigm shift in the way we collect images in a camera.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The QIS idea is in its infancy and may never become reality due to the non necessary complexity that is needed to capture an image.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Boyd Fowler of OmniVision is known for his work in CMOS image sensor development.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] He also patented the first CMOS image sensor for inter-oral dental X-rays with clipped corners for better patient comfort.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] By the late 2010s CMOS sensors had largely if not completely replaced CCD sensors, as CMOS sensors can not only be made in existing semiconductor production lines, reducing costs, but they also consume less power, just to name a few advantages.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] HV-CMOS devices are a specialty case of ordinary CMOS sensors used in high-voltage applications (for detection of high-energy particles) like CERN Large Hadron Collider where a high-breakdown voltage up to ~30-120V is necessary.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Such devices are not used for high-voltage switching though.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] HV-CMOS are typically implemented by ~10 μm deep n-doped depletion zone (n-well) of a transistor on a p-type wafer substrate.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] APS pixels solve the speed and scalability issues of the passive-pixel sensor.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] They generally consume less power than CCDs, have less image lag, and require less specialized manufacturing facilities.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Unlike CCDs, APS sensors can combine the image sensor function and image processing functions within the same integrated circuit.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] APS sensors have found markets in many consumer applications, especially camera phones.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] They have also been used in other fields including digital radiography, military ultra high speed image acquisition, security cameras, and optical mice.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Manufacturers include Aptina Imaging (independent spinout from Micron Technology, who purchased Photobit in 2001), Canon, Samsung, STMicroelectronics, Toshiba, OmniVision Technologies, Sony, and Foveon, among others.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] CMOS-type APS sensors are typically suited to applications in which packaging, power management, and on-chip processing are important.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] CMOS type sensors are widely used, from high-end digital photography down to mobile-phone cameras.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] A primary advantage of a CMOS sensor is that it is typically less expensive to produce than a CCD sensor, as the image capturing and image sensing elements can be combined onto the same IC, with simpler construction required.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] A CMOS sensor also typically has better control of blooming (that is, of bleeding of photo-charge from an over-exposed pixel into other nearby pixels).
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Unlike CCD sensors, CMOS sensors have the ability to reverse the addressing of the sensor elements.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] CMOS Sensors with a film speed of ISO 4 million exist.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Since a CMOS sensor typically captures a row at a time within approximately 1/60 or 1/50 of a second (depending on refresh rate) it may result in a rolling shutter effect, where the image is skewed (tilted to the left or right, depending on the direction of camera or subject movement).
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] For example, when tracking a car moving at high speed, the car will not be distorted but the background will appear to be tilted.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] A frame-transfer CCD sensor or "global shutter" CMOS sensor does not have this problem; instead it captures the entire image at once into a frame store.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] A long-standing advantage of CCD sensors has been their capability for capturing images with lower noise.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] With improvements in CMOS technology, this advantage has closed as of 2020, with modern CMOS sensors available capable of outperforming CCD sensors.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The active circuitry in CMOS pixels takes some area on the surface which is not light-sensitive, reducing the photon-detection efficiency of the device (microlenses and back-illuminated sensors can mitigate this problem).
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] But the frame-transfer CCD also has about half the non-sensitive area for the frame store nodes, so the relative advantages depend on which types of sensors are being compared.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The standard CMOS APS pixel consists of a photodetector (pinned photodiode), a floating diffusion, and the so-called 4T cell consisting of four CMOS (complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor) transistors, including a transfer gate, reset gate, selection gate and source-follower readout transistor.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The use of intrapixel charge transfer can offer lower noise by enabling the use of correlated double sampling (CDS).
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The Noble 3T pixel is still sometimes used since the fabrication requirements are less complex.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The 3T pixel comprises the same elements as the 4T pixel except the transfer gate and the photodiode.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The reset transistor, Mrst, acts as a switch to reset the floating diffusion to VRST, which in this case is represented as the gate of the Msf transistor.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] When the reset transistor is turned on, the photodiode is effectively connected to the power supply, VRST, clearing all integrated charge.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Since the reset transistor is n-type, the pixel operates in soft reset.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The read-out transistor, Msf, acts as a buffer (specifically, a source follower), an amplifier which allows the pixel voltage to be observed without removing the accumulated charge.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Its power supply, VDD, is typically tied to the power supply of the reset transistor VRST.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The select transistor, Msel, allows a single row of the pixel array to be read by the read-out electronics.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Other innovations of the pixels such as 5T and 6T pixels also exist.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] By adding extra transistors, functions such as global shutter, as opposed to the more common rolling shutter, are possible.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] In order to increase the pixel densities, shared-row, four-ways and eight-ways shared read out, and other architectures can be employed.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] A variant of the 3T active pixel is the Foveon X3 sensor invented by Dick Merrill.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] In this device, three photodiodes are stacked on top of each other using planar fabrication techniques, each photodiode having its own 3T circuit.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Each successive layer acts as a filter for the layer below it shifting the spectrum of absorbed light in successive layers.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] By deconvolving the response of each layered detector, red, green, and blue signals can be reconstructed.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] A typical two-dimensional array of pixels is organized into rows and columns.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Pixels in a given row share reset lines, so that a whole row is reset at a time.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The row select lines of each pixel in a row are tied together as well.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The outputs of each pixel in any given column are tied together.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Since only one row is selected at a given time, no competition for the output line occurs.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Further amplifier circuitry is typically on a column basis.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The size of the pixel sensor is often given in height and width, but also in the optical format.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] There are two types of active-pixel sensor (APS) structures, the lateral APS and vertical APS.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] For applications such as large-area digital X-ray imaging, thin-film transistors (TFTs) can also be used in APS architecture.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] However, because of the larger size and lower transconductance gain of TFTs compared with CMOS transistors, it is necessary to have fewer on-pixel TFTs to maintain image resolution and quality at an acceptable level.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] A two-transistor APS/PPS architecture has been shown to be promising for APS using amorphous silicon TFTs.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] In the two-transistor APS architecture on the right, TAMP is used as a switched-amplifier integrating functions of both Msf and Msel in the three-transistor APS.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] This results in reduced transistor counts per pixel, as well as increased pixel transconductance gain.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Here, Cpix is the pixel storage capacitance, and it is also used to capacitively couple the addressing pulse of the "Read" to the gate of TAMP for ON-OFF switching.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Such pixel readout circuits work best with low capacitance photoconductor detectors such as amorphous selenium.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Many different pixel designs have been proposed and fabricated.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The standard pixel uses the fewest wires and the fewest, most tightly packed transistors possible for an active pixel.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] It is important that the active circuitry in a pixel take up as little space as possible to allow more room for the photodetector.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] High transistor count hurts fill factor, that is, the percentage of the pixel area that is sensitive to light.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Pixel size can be traded for desirable qualities such as noise reduction or reduced image lag.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Noise is a measure of the accuracy with which the incident light can be measured.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Lag occurs when traces of a previous frame remain in future frames, i.e. the pixel is not fully reset.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The voltage noise variance in a soft-reset (gate-voltage regulated) pixel is $V_{n}^{2}=kT/2C$ , but image lag and fixed pattern noise may be problematic.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Hard reset The pixel via hard reset results in a Johnson–Nyquist noise on the photodiode of $V_{n}^{2}=kT/C$ or $N_{e}={\frac {\sqrt {kTC}}{q}}$ , but prevents image lag, sometimes a desirable tradeoff.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] One way to use hard reset is replace Mrst with a p-type transistor and invert the polarity of the RST signal.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The presence of the p-type device reduces fill factor, as extra space is required between p- and n-devices; it also removes the possibility of using the reset transistor as an overflow anti-blooming drain, which is a commonly exploited benefit of the n-type reset FET.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Another way to achieve hard reset, with the n-type FET, is to lower the voltage of VRST relative to the on-voltage of RST.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] This reduction may reduce headroom, or full-well charge capacity, but does not affect fill factor, unless VDD is then routed on a separate wire with its original voltage.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Techniques such as flushed reset, pseudo-flash reset, and hard-to-soft reset combine soft and hard reset.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The details of these methods differ, but the basic idea is the same.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] First, a hard reset is done, eliminating image lag.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Next, a soft reset is done, causing a low noise reset without adding any lag.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Pseudo-flash reset requires separating VRST from VDD, while the other two techniques add more complicated column circuitry.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Specifically, pseudo-flash reset and hard-to-soft reset both add transistors between the pixel power supplies and the actual VDD.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The result is lower headroom, without affecting fill factor.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] A more radical pixel design is the active-reset pixel.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] Active reset can result in much lower noise levels.
[src:zebra-patterning/active-pixel-sensor] The tradeoff is a complicated reset scheme, as well as either a much larger pixel or extra column-level circuitry.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Platforms for aerial photography include fixed-wing aircraft, helicopters, unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs or "drones"), balloons, blimps and dirigibles, rockets, pigeons, kites, or using action cameras while skydiving or wingsuiting.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Handheld cameras may be manually operated by the photographer, while mounted cameras are usually remotely operated or triggered automatically.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Aerial photography typically refers specifically to bird's-eye view images that focus on landscapes and surface objects, and should not be confused with air-to-air photography, where one or more aircraft are used as chase planes that "chase" and photograph other aircraft in flight.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Elevated photography can also produce bird's-eye images closely resembling aerial photography (despite not actually being aerial shots) when telephotoing from high vantage structures, suspended on cables (e.g.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Skycam) or on top of very tall poles that are either handheld (e.g. monopods and selfie sticks), fixed firmly to the ground (e.g. surveillance cameras and crane shots) or mounted above vehicles.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Aerial photography was first practiced by the French photographer and balloonist Gaspard-Félix Tournachon, known as "Nadar", in 1858 over Paris, France.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] However, the photographs he produced no longer exist and therefore the earliest surviving aerial photograph is titled 'Boston, as the Eagle and the Wild Goose See It.' Taken by James Wallace Black and Samuel Archer King on October 13, 1860, it depicts Boston from a height of 630m.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Kite aerial photography was pioneered by British meteorologist E.D.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] He used an explosive charge on a timer to take photographs from the air.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The same year, Cecil Shadbolt devised a method of taking photographs from the basket of a gas balloon, including shots looking vertically downwards.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] One of his images, taken from 2,000 feet (610 m) over Stamford Hill, is the earliest extant aerial photograph taken in the British Isles.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] A print of the same image, *An Instantaneous Map Photograph taken from the Car of a Balloon, 2,000 feet high*, was shown at the 1882 Photographic Society exhibition.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Frenchman Arthur Batut began using kites for photography in 1888, and wrote a book on his methods in 1890.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Samuel Franklin Cody developed his advanced 'Man-lifter War Kite' and succeeded in interesting the British War Office with its capabilities.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] In 1908, Albert Samama Chikly filmed the first ever aerial views using a balloon between Hammam-Lif and Grombalia.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The first use of a motion picture camera mounted to a heavier-than-air aircraft took place on April 24, 1909, over Rome in the 3:28 silent film short, *Wilbur Wright und seine Flugmaschine*.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The use of aerial photography rapidly matured during the war, as reconnaissance aircraft were equipped with cameras to record enemy movements and defenses.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] At the start of the conflict, the usefulness of aerial photography was not fully appreciated, with reconnaissance being accomplished with map sketching from the air.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Germany adopted the first aerial camera, a Görz, in 1913.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The French began the war with several squadrons of Blériot observation aircraft equipped with cameras for reconnaissance.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The French Army developed procedures for getting prints into the hands of field commanders in record time.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Frederick Charles Victor Laws started aerial photography experiments in 1912 with No.1 Squadron of the Royal Flying Corps (later No.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] 1 Squadron RAF), taking photographs from the British dirigible *Beta*.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] He discovered that vertical photos taken with a 60% overlap could be used to create a stereoscopic effect when viewed in a stereoscope, thus creating a perception of depth that could aid in cartography and in intelligence derived from aerial images.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The Royal Flying Corps recon pilots began to use cameras for recording their observations in 1914 and by the Battle of Neuve Chapelle in 1915, the entire system of German trenches was being photographed.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] In 1916, the Austro-Hungarian Monarchy made vertical camera axis aerial photos above Italy for map-making.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The first purpose-built and practical aerial camera was invented by Captain John Moore-Brabazon in 1915 with the help of the Thornton-Pickard company, greatly enhancing the efficiency of aerial photography.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The camera was inserted into the floor of the aircraft and could be triggered by the pilot at intervals.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Moore-Brabazon also pioneered the incorporation of stereoscopic techniques into aerial photography, allowing the height of objects on the landscape to be discerned by comparing photographs taken at different angles.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] In January 1918, General Allenby used five Australian pilots from No.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] 1 Squadron AFC to photograph a 624 square miles (1,620 km2) area in Palestine as an aid to correcting and improving maps of the Turkish front.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] This was a pioneering use of aerial photography as an aid for cartography.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Lieutenants Leonard Taplin, Allan Runciman Brown, H.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Rogers photographed a block of land stretching from the Turkish front lines 32 miles (51 km) deep into their rear areas.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Beginning 5 January, they flew with a fighter escort to ward off enemy fighters.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Using Royal Aircraft Factory BE.12 and Martinsyde airplanes, they not only overcame enemy air attacks, but also had to contend with 65 mph (105 km/h) winds, antiaircraft fire, and malfunctioning equipment to complete their task.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The first commercial aerial photography company in the UK was Aerofilms Ltd, founded by World War I veterans Francis Wills and Claude Graham White in 1919.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The company soon expanded into a business with major contracts in Africa and Asia as well as in the UK.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Operations began from the Stag Lane Aerodrome at Edgware, using the aircraft of the London Flying School.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Subsequently, the Aircraft Manufacturing Company (later the De Havilland Aircraft Company), hired an Airco DH.9 along with pilot entrepreneur Alan Cobham.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] From 1921, Aerofilms carried out vertical photography for survey and mapping purposes.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] During the 1930s, the company pioneered the science of photogrammetry (mapping from aerial photographs), with the Ordnance Survey amongst the company's clients.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] In 1920, the Australian Milton Kent started using a half-plate oblique aero camera purchased from Carl Zeiss AG in his aerial photographic business.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Another successful pioneer of the commercial use of aerial photography was the American Sherman Fairchild who started with his own aircraft firm Fairchild Aircraft to develop and build specialized aircraft for high altitude aerial survey missions.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] One Fairchild aerial survey aircraft in 1935 carried a unit that combined two synchronized cameras.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Utilizing two units of ten lenses each with a ten-inch lens, the aircraft took photos from 23,000 feet.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Each photo covered two hundred and twenty-five square miles.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] One of its first government contracts was an aerial survey of New Mexico to study soil erosion.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] A year later, Fairchild introduced a better high altitude camera with a nine-lens in one unit that could take a photo covering 600 square miles with each exposure from 30,000 feet.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] In 1939, Sidney Cotton and Flying Officer Maurice Longbottom of the RAF were among the first to suggest that airborne reconnaissance may be a task better suited to fast, small aircraft which would use their speed and high service ceiling to avoid detection and interception.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Although this seems obvious now, with modern reconnaissance tasks performed by fast, high flying aircraft, at the time it was radical thinking.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] They proposed the use of Spitfires with their armament and radios removed and replaced with extra fuel and cameras.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] This led to the development of the Spitfire PR variants.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Spitfires proved to be extremely successful in their reconnaissance role and there were many variants built specifically for that purpose.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] They served initially with what later became No.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] 1 Photographic Reconnaissance Unit (PRU).
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] In 1928, the RAF developed an electric heating system for the aerial camera.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] This allowed reconnaissance aircraft to take pictures from very high altitudes without the camera parts freezing.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Based at RAF Medmenham, the collection and interpretation of such photographs became a considerable enterprise.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Cotton's aerial photographs were far ahead of their time.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Together with other members of the 1 PRU, he pioneered the techniques of high-altitude, high-speed stereoscopic photography that were instrumental in revealing the locations of many crucial military and intelligence targets.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Jones, photographs were used to establish the size and the characteristic launching mechanisms for both the V-1 flying bomb and the V-2 rocket.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Cotton also worked on ideas such as a prototype specialist reconnaissance aircraft and further refinements of photographic equipment.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] At the peak, the British flew over 100 reconnaissance flights a day, yielding 50,000 images per day to interpret.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Similar efforts were taken by other countries.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] While stationed on an aircraft carrier in Imperial Japan, FS Hussain, a pilot in the Royal Indian Air Force, was tasked with photographing the aftermath of the Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Unaware of the risks of exposure to radiation, it led to his death in 1969 at the age of 44.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Vertical aerial photography is used in cartography (particularly in photogrammetric surveys, which are often the basis for topographic maps), land-use planning, aerial archaeology.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Oblique aerial photography is used for movie production, environmental studies, power line inspection, surveillance, construction progress, commercial advertising, conveyancing, and artistic projects.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] An example of how aerial photography is used in the field of archaeology is the mapping project done at the site Angkor Borei in Cambodia from 1995 to 1996.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Using aerial photography, archaeologists were able to identify archaeological features, including 112 water features (reservoirs, artificially constructed pools and natural ponds) within the walled site of Angkor Borei.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] In the United States, aerial photographs are used in many Phase I Environmental Site Assessments for property analysis.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] In the United States, except when necessary for take-off and landing, full-sized manned aircraft are prohibited from flying at altitudes under 1000 feet over congested areas and not closer than 500 feet from any person, vessel, vehicle or structure over non-congested areas.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Certain exceptions are allowed for helicopters, powered parachutes and weight-shift-control aircraft.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Advances in radio controlled models have made it possible for model aircraft to conduct low-altitude aerial photography.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] This had benefited real-estate advertising, where commercial and residential properties are the photographic subject.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] In 2014, the US Federal Aviation Administration banned the use of drones for photographs in real estate advertisements.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The ban has been lifted and commercial aerial photography using drones of UAS is regulated under the FAA Reauthorization Act of 2018.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Commercial pilots have to complete the requirements for a Part 107 license, while amateur and non-commercial use is restricted by the FAA.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Small scale model aircraft offer increased photographic access to these previously restricted areas.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Miniature vehicles do not replace full-size aircraft, as full-size aircraft are capable of longer flight times, higher altitudes, and greater equipment payloads.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] They are, however, useful in any situation in which a full-scale aircraft would be dangerous to operate.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Examples would include the inspection of transformers atop power transmission lines and slow, low-level flight over agricultural fields, both of which can be accomplished by a large-scale radio-controlled helicopter.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Professional-grade, gyroscopically stabilized camera platforms are available for use under such a model; a large model helicopter with a 26cc gasoline engine can hoist a payload of approximately seven kilograms (15 pounds).
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] One example is the radio controlled Nitrohawk helicopter developed by Robert Channon between 1988 and 1998.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] In addition to gyroscopically stabilized footage, the use of RC copters as reliable aerial photography tools increased with the integration of FPV (first-person-view) technology.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Many radio-controlled aircraft, in particular drones, are now capable of utilizing Wi-Fi to stream live video from the aircraft's camera back to the pilot's or pilot in command's (PIC) ground station.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] In Australia, Civil Aviation Safety Regulation Part 101 (CASR Part 101) allows for commercial use of unmanned and remotely piloted aircraft.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Under these regulations, unmanned remotely piloted aircraft for commercial are referred to as Remotely Piloted Aircraft Systems (RPAS), whereas radio-controlled aircraft for recreational purposes are referred to as model aircraft.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Under CASR Part 101, businesses/persons operating remotely piloted aircraft commercially are required to hold an operator certificate, just like manned aircraft operators.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Pilots of remotely piloted aircraft operating commercially are also required to be licensed by the Civil Aviation Safety Authority (CASA).
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] While a small RPAS and model aircraft may actually be identical, unlike model aircraft, a RPAS may enter controlled airspace with approval, and operate close to an aerodrome.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Due to a number of illegal operators in Australia, making false claims of being approved, CASA maintains and publishes a list of approved remote operator's certificate (ReOC) holders.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] However, CASA has modified the regulations and from September 29, 2016, drones under 2 kg (4.4 lb) may be operated for commercial purposes.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] 2006 FAA regulations grounding all commercial RC model flights have been upgraded to require formal FAA certification before permission is granted to fly at any altitude in the US.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] On June 25, 2014, the FAA, in ruling 14 CFR Part 91 [Docket No.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] FAA–2014–0396] "Interpretation of the Special Rule for Model Aircraft", banned the commercial use of unmanned aircraft over U.S. airspace.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] On September 26, 2014, the FAA began granting the right to use drones in aerial filmmaking.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Operators are required to be licensed pilots and must keep the drone in view at all times.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Drones cannot be used to film in areas where people might be put at risk.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The FAA Modernization and Reform Act of 2012 established, in Section 336, a special rule for model aircraft.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] In Section 336, Congress confirmed the FAA's long-standing position that model aircraft are aircraft.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Because anything capable of being viewed from a public space is considered outside the realm of privacy in the United States, aerial photography may legally document features and occurrences on private property.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The FAA can pursue enforcement action against persons operating model aircraft who endanger the safety of the national airspace system: Public Law 112–95, section 336(b).
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] On June 21, 2016, the FAA released its summary of small unmanned aircraft rules (Part 107).
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The rules established guidelines for small UAS operators including operating only during the daytime, a 400 ft (120 m). ceiling and pilots must keep the UAS in visual range.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] On April 7, 2017, the FAA announced special security instructions under 14 CFR § 99.7.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Effective April 14, 2017, all UAS flights within 400 feet of the lateral boundaries of U.S. military installations are prohibited unless a special permit is secured from the base and/or the FAA.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Aerial photography in the UK has tight regulations as to where a drone is able to fly.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Aerial Photography on Light aircraft under 20 kg (44 lb).
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Basic Rules for non commercial flying Of a SUA (Small Unmanned Aircraft).
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Article 241 Endangering safety of any person or property states that a person must not recklessly or negligently cause or permit an aircraft to endanger any person or property.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The person in charge of a small unmanned aircraft may only fly the aircraft if reasonably satisfied that the flight can safely be made.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The person in charge of a small unmanned aircraft must maintain direct, unaided visual contact with the aircraft sufficient to monitor its flight path in relation to other aircraft, persons, vehicles, vessels and structures for the purpose of avoiding collisions.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The person in charge of a small unmanned aircraft must not fly the aircraft for the purposes of commercial operations except in accordance with a permission granted by the CAA.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Over or within 150 m (490 ft) of an organised open-air assembly of more than 1,000 persons.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Within 50 m (160 ft) of any vessel, vehicle or structure which is not under the control of the person in charge of the aircraft.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Within 50 m of any person, during take-off or landing, a small unmanned surveillance aircraft must not be flown within 30 m (98 ft) of any person.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] This does not apply to the person in charge of the small unmanned surveillance aircraft or a person under the control of the person in charge of the aircraft.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Model aircraft with a mass of more than 20 kg are termed 'Large Model Aircraft' – within the UK, large model aircraft may only be flown in accordance with an exemption from the ANO, which must be issued by the CAA.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Photographs taken at an angle are called *oblique photographs*.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] If they are taken from a low angle relative to the earth's surface, they are called *low oblique* and photographs taken from a high angle are called *high* or *steep oblique*.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Vertical photographs are taken straight down.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] They are mainly used in photogrammetry and image interpretation.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Pictures that will be used in photogrammetry are traditionally taken with special large format cameras with calibrated and documented geometric properties.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Depending on their purpose, it can be done in several ways, of which a few are listed below.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Vertical photographs are often used to create orthophotos, alternatively known as orthophotomaps, photographs which have been geometrically "corrected" so as to be usable as a map.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] In other words, an orthophoto is a simulation of a photograph taken from an infinite distance, looking straight down to nadir.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Perspective must obviously be removed, but variations in terrain should also be corrected for.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Multiple geometric transformations are applied to the image, depending on the perspective and terrain corrections required on a particular part of the image.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Orthophotos are commonly used in geographic information systems, such as are used by mapping agencies (e.g.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Once the images have been aligned, or "registered", with known real-world coordinates, they can be widely deployed.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Large sets of orthophotos, typically derived from multiple sources and divided into "tiles" (each typically 256 x 256 pixels in size), are widely used in online map systems such as Google Maps.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] OpenStreetMap offers the use of similar orthophotos for deriving new map data.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Google Earth overlays orthophotos or satellite imagery onto a digital elevation model to simulate 3D landscapes.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Aerial photography may be labeled as either "leaf-off" or on "leaf-on" to indicate whether deciduous foliage is in the photograph.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Leaf-off photographs show less foliage or no foliage at all, and are used to see the ground and things on the ground more closely.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Leaf-on photographs are used to measure crop health and yield.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] For forestry purposes, some species of trees are easier to distinguish from other kinds of trees with leaf-off photography, while other species are easier to distinguish with leaf-on photography.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] With advancements in video technology, aerial video is becoming more popular.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Orthogonal video is shot from aircraft mapping pipelines, crop fields, and other points of interest.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Using GPS, video may be embedded with meta data and later synced with a video mapping program.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] This "Spatial Multimedia" is the timely union of digital media including still photography, motion video, stereo, panoramic imagery sets, immersive media constructs, audio, and other data with location and date-time information from the GPS and other location designs.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Aerial videos are emerging Spatial Multimedia which can be used for scene understanding and object tracking.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The input video is captured by low flying aerial platforms and typically consists of strong parallax from non-ground-plane structures.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] The integration of digital video, global positioning systems (GPS) and automated image processing will improve the accuracy and cost-effectiveness of data collection and reduction.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] Several different aerial platforms are under investigation for the data collection.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] In film production, it is common to use a unmanned aerial vehicle with a mounted cine camera.
[src:zebra-patterning/aerial-photography] For example, the AERIGON cinema drone is used for low aerial shots in big blockbuster movies.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] Afocal photography works with any system that can produce a virtual image of parallel light, for example telescopes and microscopes.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] Afocal photographic setups work because the imaging device's eyepiece produces collimated light and with the camera's lens focused at infinity, creating an afocal system with no net convergence or divergence in the light path between the two devices.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] In this system the device is focused on the object and the camera is placed above the eyepiece as close as possible.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] The drawback is the system will have a high focal ratio, with a correspondingly dim image, and some vignetting.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] A high focal ratio also means the field of view will be narrow.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] One method of afocal photography is to mount a camera with its lens attached behind the eyepiece of a Keplerian optical telescope, the combination giving the photographer a long focus lens.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] Historically afocal photography with 35 mm SLR or large format film cameras was a very difficult method of photography.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] With film cameras the bulk and mechanical shake had to be taken into consideration, with some setups employing a separate tripod for the camera (adding the complexity of setting up the camera in relation to the eyepiece).
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] The general difficulties of focus and exposure with film cameras, along with the detailed mathematical calculations, combined with the time lag of waiting for the film to be developed, made film afocal photography challenging.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] Couplers and other devices for mounting digital cameras afocally are commercially available.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] Simply holding the camera up to the eyepiece and snapping a picture can obtain usable results.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] Most popular types of consumer digital cameras have non-removable lenses so afocal photography is also the only method available for these types of cameras.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] Afocal photography is a form of astrophotography long practiced by astronomers.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] Almost from their invention amateur astronomers were adapting compact digital still and video cameras for use in afocal astrophotography.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] But since most celestial objects require a long exposure, compact consumer digital cameras are somewhat problematic due to their high inherent sensor noise.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] This noise limits their usefulness, especially since point-objects, such as stars, can be obscured by even one "hot" pixel.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] The narrow field of view for this type of photography lends itself to lunar and planetary objects.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] Continuing advancements in digital camera and image manipulation have somewhat overcome this limitation and digital afocal astrophotography has become more popular.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] Since the development of compact digital cameras, afocal photography is also widely used by birdwatchers, naturalists, and other photographers.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] In the birdwatching community it quickly acquired the coined name of “digiscoping”.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] Since these types of photographs are usually single subjects (narrow field) in daylight hours, the light loss and narrow angle of view are not a hindrance, and the high effective focal lengths are beneficial.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] It also facilitates the use of a very long lens without buying and transporting extra equipment, other than perhaps a small afocal adapter.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] Besides combining a Keplerian telescope with a camera, there are also dedicated secondary lens afocal attachments that mount on the front of a camera lens to work in the role of a teleconverter, technically called teleside converters.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] These lenses are usually Galilean telescopes that alter the width of the entering beam of light without affecting the divergence of the beam, so they can change the effective focal length 1 to 3 times without increasing focal ratio.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] There are models that are 6x or 8x and even Russian made 12x to 14x Gregorian Maksutov designs that can be used as long lenses and microscopes.
[src:zebra-patterning/afocal-photography] Like their Keplerian counterparts these can be universally adapted to most camera lenses with the proper type of adapter.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Aviation enthusiasts have been watching airplanes and other aircraft since aviation began.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] However, as a hobby (distinct from active/wartime work), planespotting did not appear until the second half of the 20th century.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] During World War II and the subsequent Cold War, some countries encouraged their citizens to become "planespotters" in an "observation corps" or similar public body for reasons of public security.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Britain had the Royal Observer Corps which operated between 1925 and 1995.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] A journal called *The Aeroplane Spotter* was published in January 1940.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] The publication included a glossary that was refined in 2010 and published online.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] The development of technology and global resources enabled a revolution in planespotting.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Point and shoot cameras, DSLRs and walkie talkies have significantly changed the hobby.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] With the help of the internet, websites such as FlightAware and Flightradar24 have made it possible for planespotters to track and locate specific aircraft around the world.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Websites such as airliners.net, JetPhotos, Instagram and YouTube allow spotters to upload their photos or videos of their sightings and share them with viewers worldwide.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] When spotting aircraft, observers generally notice the key attributes of an aircraft, such as a distinctive noise from its engine, the number of contrails it is producing, or its callsign.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Observers can also assess the size of the aircraft and the number, type, and position of its engines.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Another distinctive attribute is the position of wings relative to the fuselage and the degree to which they are swept rearwards.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] The wings may be above the fuselage, below it, or fixed at midpoint.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] The number of wings indicates whether it is a monoplane, biplane or triplane.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] The position of the tailplane relative to the fin(s) and the shape of the fin are other attributes.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] The configuration of the landing gear can be distinctive, as well as the size and shape of the cockpit and passenger windows along with the layout of emergency exits and doors.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Other features include the speed, cockpit placement, colour scheme or special equipment that changes the silhouette of the aircraft.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Taken together these traits will enable the identification of an aircraft.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] If the observer is familiar with the airfield being used by the aircraft and its normal traffic patterns, they are more likely to leap quickly to a decision about the aircraft's identity – they may have seen the same type of aircraft from the same angle many times.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] This is particularly prevalent if the aircraft spotter is spotting commercial aircraft, operated by airlines that have a limited fleet.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Spotters use equipment such as ADS-B decoders to track the movements of aircraft.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] The two most famous devices used are the AirNav Systems RadarBox and Kinetic Avionics SBS series.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Both of them read and process the radar data and show the movements on a computer screen.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Another tool that spotters can use are apps such as FlightRadar24 or Flightaware, where they can look at arrival and departure schedules and track the location of aircraft that have their transponder on.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Most of the decoders also allow the exporting of logs from a certain route or airport.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Some spotters will note and compile the markings, a national insignia or airline livery or logo, a squadron badge or code letters in the case of a military aircraft.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Published manuals allow more information to be deduced, such as the delivery date or the manufacturer's construction number.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Camouflage markings differ, depending on the surroundings in which that aircraft is expected to operate.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] In general, most spotters attempt to see as many aircraft of a given type, a particular airline, or a particular subset of aircraft such as business jets, commercial airliners, military and/or general aviation aircraft.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Some spotters attempt to see every airframe and are known as "frame spotters." Others are keen to see every registration worn by each aircraft.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Ancillary activities might include listening-in to air traffic control transmissions (using radio scanners, where that is legal), liaising with other "spotters" to clear up uncertainties as to what aircraft have been seen at specific times or in particular places.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Several internet mailing list groups have been formed to help communicate aircraft seen at airports, queries and anomalies.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] These groups can cater to certain regions, certain aircraft types, or may appeal to a wider audience.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] The result is that information on aircraft movements can be delivered worldwide in a real-time fashion to spotters.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] The hobbyist might travel long distances to visit different airports, to see an unusual aircraft, or to view the remains of aircraft withdrawn from use.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Air shows usually draw large numbers of spotters as they are opportunities to enter airfields and air bases worldwide that are usually closed to the public and to see displayed aircraft at close range.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Some aircraft may be placed in the care of museums (see Aviation archaeology) – or perhaps be cannibalized in order to repair a similar aircraft already preserved.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Aircraft registrations can be found in books, with online resources, or in monthly magazines from enthusiast groups.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Most spotters maintained books of different aircraft fleets and would underline or check each aircraft seen.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Each year, a revised version of the books would be published and the spotter would need to re-underline every aircraft seen.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] With the development of commercial aircraft databases spotters were finally able to record their sightings in an electronic database and produce reports that emulated the underlined books.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Thanks to the Internet and live video streaming, planespotters are now able to watch departure and arrival traffic from anywhere in the world with Internet access.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Airline Videos Live, based in Los Angeles at LAX and streaming since 2019, offers several days of streaming weekly on their exclusive YouTube channel in a highly polished format, manned by "The Plane Jockeys".
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] In addition to LAX, AVL also streams from airports such as San Francisco (SFO), New York (JFK), Phoenix (PHX) and even Sint Maarten, and have a following more than 830,000 subscribers, dwarfing the smaller streaming channels in the area.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] The legal repercussions of the hobby were dramatically shown in November 2001 when fourteen aircraft spotters (twelve British, two Dutch) were arrested by Greek police after being observed at an open day at the Greek Air Force base at Kalamata.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] They were charged with espionage and faced a possible 20-year prison sentence if found guilty.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] After being held for six weeks, they were eventually released on $11,696 (£9,000) bail, and the charges reduced to the misdemeanor charge of illegal information collection.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] They returned for their trial in April 2002 and were found guilty, with eight of the group sentenced to three years, the rest for one year.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] At their appeal a year later, all were acquitted.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] In the wake of the targeting of airports by terrorists, enthusiasts' organisations and police in the UK have cooperated in creating a code of conduct for planespotters, in a similar vein to guidelines devised for train spotters.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] By asking enthusiasts to contact police if spotters believe they see or hear something suspicious, this is an attempt to allow enthusiasts to continue their hobby while increasing security around airports.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Birmingham and Stansted pioneered this approach in Britain and prior to the 2012 London Olympics, RAF Northolt introduced a *Flightwatch* scheme based on the same cooperative principles.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] These changes are also being made abroad in countries such as Australia, where aviation enthusiasts are reporting suspicious or malicious actions to police.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] The organisation of such groups has now been echoed in parts of North America.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] For example, the Bensenville, Illinois police department have sponsored an *Airport Watch* group at the Chicago O'Hare Airport.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Members are issued identification cards and given training to accurately record and report unusual activities around the airport perimeter.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] (Members are not permitted airside.) Meetings are attended and supported by the FBI, Chicago Department of Aviation and the TSA who also provide regular training to group members.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] The Bensenville program was modeled on similar programs in Toronto, Ottawa and Minneapolis.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] In 2009, a similar airport watch group was organized between airport security and local aircraft spotters at Montréal–Pierre Elliott Trudeau International Airport.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] As of 2016, the group has 46 members and a special phone number to use to contact police if suspicious activity is seen around the airport area.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Following the events of 9/11, information collected by planespotters helped uncover what is known as *extraordinary rendition* by the CIA.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] Information on unusual movements of rendition aircraft provided data that was mapped by critical geographers such as Trevor Paglen and the Institute for Applied Autonomy.
[src:zebra-patterning/aircraft-spotting] These data and maps led first to news reports and then to a number of governmental and inter-governmental investigations.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] The **albumen print**, also called **albumen silver print**, is a method of producing a photographic print using egg whites.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] Published in January 1847 by Louis Désiré Blanquart-Evrard, it was the first commercial process of producing a photo on a paper base from a negative, previous methods—such as the daguerreotype and the tintype—having been printed on metal.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] It became the dominant form of photographic positives from 1855 to the start of the 20th century, with a peak in the 1860–1890 period.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] During the mid-19th century, the carte de visite became one of the more popular uses of the albumen method.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] Anthony & Company were the largest makers and distributors of albumen photographic prints and paper in the United States.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] The paper is then dipped in a solution of silver nitrate and water, which renders the surface sensitive to UV light.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] The paper is then dried in the absence of UV light.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] The dried, prepared paper is placed in a frame in direct contact under a negative.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] The negative is traditionally a glass negative with collodion emulsion, but this step can be performed with a modern silver halide negative, too.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] The paper with the negative is then exposed to light until the image achieves the desired level of darkness, which is typically a little lighter than the end product.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] The progress of the print can be checked during the exposure, as it is a printing-out process, and the image can be seen taking form as it is being exposed to light.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] Though direct sunlight was used long ago, a UV exposure unit is often used contemporarily because it is more predictable, as the paper is most sensitive to ultraviolet light.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] A bath of sodium thiosulfate fixes the print's exposure, preventing further darkening.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] Optional gold or selenium toning improves the photograph's tone and stabilizes against fading.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] Depending on the toner, toning may be performed before or after fixing the print.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] Because the image emerges as a direct result of exposure to light, without the aid of a developing solution, an albumen print may be said to be a *printed* rather than a developed photograph.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] The table salt (sodium chloride) in the albumen emulsion forms silver chloride when in contact with silver nitrate.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] Silver chloride is unstable when exposed to light, which makes it decompose into silver and chlorine.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] The silver ion (Ag+) is reduced to silver (Ag) by the addition of an electron during the development/printing process, and the remaining silver chloride is washed out during fixing.
[src:zebra-patterning/albumen-print] The black parts of the image are formed by metallic silver (Ag).
[src:zebra-patterning/zebra-patterning] Often, a threshold level can be set, e.g.
[src:zebra-patterning/zebra-patterning] A lower threshold like 70 to 80% can help correctly expose many skin tones, while higher numbers help ensure correct overall scene exposure.
